The queen after he had looked a while upon him, and aw his eyes wim in tears; 
                     erances (aid he unto him) all that I can gather from your dicoure, is, that my on is lot, and that there is no hopes ever to ee him again. And 
                     erances making no reply, but adly haking his houlders, Oh Gods! aid he, mut the Sybil be a Liar only unto me? Here is thy prediction, oh Meluine (aid he, and pulled a paper out of her pocket) written with thy own hand; I mut to my grief upbraid thee with it, and tell the world thou art an Impotor, a Deceiver, and not to be believed. The King then taking the paper, and reading it he did admire it, that the Sybil hould o foreee all that hapned unto her on, and the incetuous marriage which was intended: But when he read thee words,
